<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41024d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41024d">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41024d"> 24(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the great Thunderer</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It was difficult to believe how any sensible person, to say nothing of the distinguished men who controlled the great &ldquo;Thunderer,&rdquo; could have swallowed the fairy tales told by Pigott in his descriptions of how he acquired the &ldquo;incriminating documents.&rdquo; Note: The Times was given the nickname &lsquo;The Thunderer&rsquo; as the result of an article by its editor, Thomas Barnes, published on 11 February 1830, in which he wrote of the paper having &lsquo;thundered out&rsquo; a sensational article. This drew a response from the Morning Herald, which referred to The Times as &lsquo;<mark>The Great</mark> Earwigger of the Nation <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> otherwise <mark>The Thunderer</mark> &mdash; but more commonly called The Blunderer&rsquo;. <small> J.B. Hall, <a name="HRRR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HRRR"><cite title="source">Random Records of a Reporter</cite></a> (n.d.) &lsquo;The Times&apos; Parnell Commission&rsquo; 212</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
